<br>
---------------------<br>
<br>
I've seen a few posts about our pet heals.  Usually, it's something along the lines of &quot;Mage heals don't cause aggro!&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, that's true -- but it's not quite the complete picture.<br>
<br>
Healing a pet does not cause aggro.<br>
<br>
Just before posting this, I tested one more time to be sure (scenarios tested 9/24 at 1PM CT).  Here's what I did:<br>
<br>
Scenario 1<br>
---------------<br>
I let my pet solo 2 mushrooms.  On the second, I gave it some help...I wanted it to have low health, but not die!  After the second shroom, my pet had about 17% health.<br>
<br>
I pulled another shroom using Shock of Blades (35 damage, unfocused).  I had the pet attack the mushroom.  With a druid, I chain Superior Healed my pet to full.  It took me 7 casts to cross 100%.  I then moved the druid to stand on top of the shroom.  It stayed on the pet.  I then sat down on top of the shroom.  It stayed on the pet.  It never attacked the druid once!<br>
<br>
Scenario 2<br>
--------------<br>
I pulled again.  This time, I started with a pet at full health.  After the pet beat the mushroom down to 50%, I walked the druid up to the mushroom.  I hit attack on and then back off.  This resulted in a miss.  The shroom immediately switched to the druid.<br>
<br>
I moved the druid out of melee range and waited until the mob was about 10%.  I moved the druid back into melee range (I did not attack again...and the druid had cast no spells while waiting) and the shroom again switched to attack the druid.<br>
<br>
Clearly, the shroom could understand an action against it.<br>
<br>
Scenario 3<br>
--------------<br>
Another pull.  Again, pet at full health...but Nenelar wasn't thanks to mod rods.  I sent the pet to attack and healed Nenelar with the druid.  It took only 2 Superior Heals to return Nenelar to full health -- far fewer than what were cast on the pet in Scenario 1.<br>
<br>
As soon as I moved the druid into melee range, the mushroom switched to attack the druid.<br>
<br>
So Superior Heal can cause aggro if cast on a player (we already knew this...but it was necessary to prove that mushrooms were not special in terms of heals and aggro).<br>
<br>
Scenario 4<br>
-------------<br>
I repeated Scenario 1 with an important difference.  I never got the druid close enough to the mushroom for the druid to get on the shroom's hate list due to proximity.  Like before, I chain-healed a near dead pet to full with the druid.  And then sat the druid down within healing range, but still far enough away not to cause a proximity aggro.<br>
<br>
Then, I gated Nenelar out of the zone.<br>
<br>
This of course killed the pet and took Nenelar off of the mushroom's hate list.<br>
<br>
What happened?  The mushroom went home -- totally ignoring the druid that had just chain healed the pet that was killing it...and was sitting roughly 100 units away.<br>
<br>
-----------------<br>
<br>
I've had similar observations in other zones with a cleric CHing my pet -- but I didn't test as precisely as above.<br>
<br>
I conclude that healing a pet is ignored by mobs in terms of hate.  Magician heals aren't special in this regard -- a druid, cleric, shaman, ranger...whomever can heal...can heal a pet without getting hate for it.<br>
<br>
Further, we are on the hate list of whatever our pets attack -- but another player can heal the pet and stay off that hate list.  Interesting, no?<br>
<br>
Have a different point of view or evidence?  Please let me know...<br>
<br>
