<br>
Here's a way to prove it:<br>
<br>
What you need: 2 similar level tanks of the same class<br>
<br>
1) DS TankA <br>
2) TankA should sit/proximity aggro a mid-level mob that hates everyone (one that can be tanked a long time...4kish mobs are good).  TankA should not fight back, nor taunt.  TankA should face away from the mob to avoid ripostle.<br>
3) Let the mob beat itself half to death on TankA<br>
4) Have TankB step in and swing a few rounds at the mob.<br>
<br>
Guess what will happen?  Despite the mob burning itself for 2k on the DS, it will switch to TankB after only a few swings.<br>
<br>
Why?  The 2k damage from the DS did not add to the hate the mob felt for TankA.  It still had only a small amount of hate for TankA based on the initial decision to attack (sitting near it or general proximity).<br>
<br>
There are a few important notes here:<br>
<br>
1) Cast the DS before the pull.  Casting the DS after the pull puts the mage on the hate list.<br>
<br>
2) Use tanks of similar level and class -- this emliminates the level and HP/AC components of hate.<br>
<br>
